<subSubSection id="18DF898CFFB6656146D0FEFEFE09FD65" pageId="5" pageNumber="406" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="507ADA07FFB6656146D0FEFEFE09FD65" blockId="5.[151,1437,151,1112]" pageId="5" pageNumber="406">
<emphasis id="62B10615FFB6656146D0FEFEFEB5FEF0" bold="true" box="[199,304,332,357]" pageId="5" pageNumber="406">Remark.</emphasis>
The width of blackish transverse lines and shadows of the forewing are highly variable; the forewing discal spot in females varies from three dots to a whole V-like spot; the hindwing ground color varies from reddish brown with a fuscous suffusion to almost black. The dark form of the species has been recently described as 
<taxonomicName id="97C5A184FFB665614680FE0BFD1EFE45" authority="N. Singh &amp; Kirti, 2016" authorityName="N. Singh &amp; Kirti" authorityYear="2016" box="[151,667,439,464]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Barsine" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fuscobarsine">
<emphasis id="62B10615FFB665614680FE0BFE03FE45" box="[151,390,439,464]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="406">Barsine fuscobarsine</emphasis>
N. Singh &amp; Kirti, 2016
</taxonomicName>
(Kirti &amp; Singh 2016). Both 
<typeStatus id="8F7E64A5FFB6656145F1FE05FBCDFE45" box="[998,1096,439,464]" pageId="5" pageNumber="406">holotype</typeStatus>
and 
<typeStatus id="8F7E64A5FFB665614294FE0AFB61FE45" box="[1155,1252,440,464]" pageId="5" pageNumber="406">paratype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="97C5A184FFB66561431AFE05FA19FE45" authorityName="N. Singh &amp; Kirti" authorityYear="2016" box="[1293,1436,439,464]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Barsine" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fuscobarsine">
<emphasis id="62B10615FFB66561431AFE05FA19FE45" box="[1293,1436,439,464]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="406">fuscobarsine</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have the hindwings black with a slight reddish-brownish suffusion, whereas the 
<typeStatus id="8F7E64A5FFB665614231FE6EFB0DFE60" box="[1062,1160,476,501]" pageId="5" pageNumber="406">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="97C5A184FFB6656142A7FE6EFA85FE61" authorityName="HAmpSON" authorityYear="1891" box="[1200,1280,476,500]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Lyclene" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="suffusa">
<emphasis id="62B10615FFB6656142A7FE6EFA85FE61" box="[1200,1280,476,500]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="406">suffusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the other specimens examined have the reddish brown hindwings with a fuscous suffusion. Nevertheless, the male genitalia of the 
<typeStatus id="8F7E64A5FFB6656146C8FD96FEC4FDA8" box="[223,321,548,573]" pageId="5" pageNumber="406">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="97C5A184FFB665614770FD96FC93FDA9" authority="(Kirti &amp; Singh 2016: 84)" authorityName="Kirti &amp; Singh" authorityPageNumber="84" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="Kirti &amp; Singh" baseAuthorityYear="2016" box="[359,790,548,573]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Barsine" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fuscobarsine">
<emphasis id="62B10615FFB665614770FD96FE73FDA8" box="[359,502,548,573]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="406">fuscobarsine</emphasis>
(Kirti &amp; Singh 2016: 84)
</taxonomicName>
have no differences from those of the paler specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="97C5A184FFB665614680FDFAFF63FDF5" authorityName="HAmpSON" authorityYear="1891" box="[151,230,584,608]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Lyclene" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="suffusa">
<emphasis id="62B10615FFB665614680FDFAFF63FDF5" box="[151,230,584,608]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="406">suffusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
therefore here we synonymize 
<taxonomicName id="97C5A184FFB66561445AFDFBFCBEFDF5" baseAuthorityName="Kirti &amp; Singh" baseAuthorityYear="2016" box="[589,827,583,608]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Barsine" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fuscobarsine">
<emphasis id="62B10615FFB66561445AFDFBFCBEFDF5" box="[589,827,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="406">Barsine fuscobarsine</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with 
<taxonomicName id="97C5A184FFB665614569FDF5FBE9FDF5" baseAuthorityName="Hampson" baseAuthorityYear="1891" box="[894,1132,583,608]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Nephelomilta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="suffusa">
<emphasis id="62B10615FFB665614569FDF5FBE9FDF5" box="[894,1132,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="406">Nephelomilta suffusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="97C5A184FFB66561435BFDFAFA1EFDF5" baseAuthorityName="Hampson" baseAuthorityYear="1891" box="[1356,1435,584,608]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Nephelomilta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="suffusa">
<emphasis id="62B10615FFB66561435BFDFAFA1EFDF5" box="[1356,1435,584,608]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="406">suffusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the 
<collectionCode id="36D442C2FFB665614715FDDFFEE9FD11" box="[258,364,621,644]" country="United Kingdom" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34665" name="Natural History Museum, London" pageId="5" pageNumber="406">NHMUK</collectionCode>
collection, including the 
<typeStatus id="8F7E64A5FFB665614486FDDEFD73FD10" box="[657,758,620,645]" pageId="5" pageNumber="406">holotype</typeStatus>
, are old and have the reddish coloration almost completely faded. Nevertheless, in the original description of 
<taxonomicName id="97C5A184FFB6656144D8FD3DFBC1FD3D" authority=", Hampson (1891)" authorityName="Hampson" authorityYear="1891" box="[719,1092,655,680]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Lyclene" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="suffisa">
<emphasis id="62B10615FFB6656144D8FD3DFCF2FD3D" box="[719,887,655,680]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="406">Lyclene suffisa</emphasis>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="3454A7F6FFB665614591FD22FBC1FD3D" box="[902,1092,656,680]" pageId="5" pageNumber="406" refId="ref28703" refString="HAmpSON, G. F. (1891) PART 8. The LepIDOpTeRA Of HeTeROCeRA Of The NILgIRI DISTRICT. Illustrations of typical specimens of Lepidoptera Heterocera in the collection of the British Museum, 8, 1 - 144, pLS. 139 - 156." type="journal article">Hampson (1891)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
describes its forewing ground color as 'pale red'. The real reddish coloration is well-visible in the fresh 
<typeStatus id="8F7E64A5FFB6656145EEFD06FBDEFD58" box="[1017,1115,692,717]" pageId="5" pageNumber="406">holotype</typeStatus>
and 
<typeStatus id="8F7E64A5FFB66561428DFD07FB7FFD58" box="[1178,1274,693,717]" pageId="5" pageNumber="406">paratype</typeStatus>
specimens of 
<emphasis id="62B10615FFB665614680FD6BFE09FD65" box="[151,396,727,752]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="406">
<taxonomicName id="97C5A184FFB665614680FD6BFE0DFD65" baseAuthorityName="Kirti &amp; Singh" baseAuthorityYear="2016" box="[151,392,727,752]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Barsine" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fuscobarsine">Barsine fuscobarsine</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="18DF898CFFB6656146D0FD4EFEBCFBA0" pageId="5" pageNumber="406" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="507ADA07FFB6656146D0FD4EFEBCFBA0" blockId="5.[151,1437,151,1112]" pageId="5" pageNumber="406">
<emphasis id="62B10615FFB6656146D0FD4EFEBFFC80" bold="true" box="[199,314,764,789]" pageId="5" pageNumber="406">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Length of forewing is 
<quantity id="973D77E2FFB665614444FD4EFD67FC81" box="[595,738,764,789]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.125" metricValueMax="1.15" metricValueMin="1.1" pageId="5" pageNumber="406" unit="mm" value="11.25" valueMax="11.5" valueMin="11.0">11–11.5 mm</quantity>
in males and 
<quantity id="973D77E2FFB66561459CFD4EFBB5FC81" box="[907,1072,764,789]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" metricValueMax="1.25" metricValueMin="1.15" pageId="5" pageNumber="406" unit="mm" value="12.0" valueMax="12.5" valueMin="11.5">11.5–12.5 mm</quantity>
in females. The species differs externally from all other congeners by its forewings with the reddish ground color and the fuscous pattern, and the hindwings black or brown with the fuscous suffusion. In the male genitalia, the shape of the valve resembles that of members of the 
<taxonomicName id="97C5A184FFB665614775FCDBFD84FC15" baseAuthorityName="van Eecke" baseAuthorityYear="1927" box="[354,513,873,896]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Nephelomilta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sumatrana">
<emphasis id="62B10615FFB665614775FCDBFD84FC15" box="[354,513,873,896]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="406">N. sumatrana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-group, but the sacculus lacks the subapical process, and the medial diverticulum is broad and short, without spines. The female genitalia are similar to those of the 
<taxonomicName id="97C5A184FFB665614317FC3FFA19FC31" baseAuthorityName="van Eecke" baseAuthorityYear="1927" box="[1280,1436,909,932]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Nephelomilta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sumatrana">
<emphasis id="62B10615FFB665614317FC3FFA19FC31" box="[1280,1436,909,932]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="406">N. sumatrana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-group due to their small pheromone glands and absence of an antevaginal plate, but the ductus bursae is evenly sclerotized and the apophyses anteriores are significantly shorter than the apophyses posteriores (whereas in the 
<taxonomicName id="97C5A184FFB6656146DDFC4BFEE8FB85" baseAuthorityName="van Eecke" baseAuthorityYear="1927" box="[202,365,1017,1040]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Nephelomilta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sumatrana">
<emphasis id="62B10615FFB6656146DDFC4BFEE8FB85" box="[202,365,1017,1040]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="406">N. sumatrana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-group the antrum is sclerotized, and the anterior section of ductus bursae is membranous).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="18DF898CFFB6656146D0FB8DFCA0FBCD" box="[199,805,1087,1112]" pageId="5" pageNumber="406" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="507ADA07FFB6656146D0FB8DFCA0FBCD" blockId="5.[151,1437,151,1112]" box="[199,805,1087,1112]" pageId="5" pageNumber="406">
<emphasis id="62B10615FFB6656146D0FB8DFEDCFBCD" bold="true" box="[199,345,1087,1112]" pageId="5" pageNumber="406">Distribution</emphasis>
. The species is known from South 
<collectingCountry id="28D29A97FFB6656144F3FB8DFCA4FBCD" box="[740,801,1087,1112]" name="India" pageId="5" pageNumber="406">India</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
